## The Camel Division Problem: An Introduction
ଓଡ଼ିଆ: ଏହି ଅଧ୍ୟାୟରେ, ଆମେ ତିନି ଭାଇଙ୍କ ମଧ୍ୟରେ ଓଟ ବଣ୍ଟନର ଏକ ରୋଚକ ସମସ୍ୟା ଏବଂ ଏହାର ଚତୁର ସମାଧାନ ବିଷୟରେ ଜାଣିବା। ଏହା ଗଣିତର ଯାଦୁକୁ ଦର୍ଶାଏ।

This lesson introduces a classic problem involving the division (ବଣ୍ଟନ) of camels according to a father's will. It highlights how a seemingly difficult mathematical problem can be solved with a clever approach, demonstrating the "magic of knowing mathematics." The story involves three brothers, a herd of 35 camels, and a young, wise "math-man" who helps resolve their dispute (ବିବାଦ).

## The Father's Will and the Initial Problem
ଓଡ଼ିଆ: ଜଣେ ପିତା ତାଙ୍କର ୩୫ଟି ଓଟକୁ ତାଙ୍କ ତିନି ପୁଅଙ୍କ ମଧ୍ୟରେ ଭାଗ କରିବା ପାଇଁ ଏକ ଇଚ୍ଛାପତ୍ର (will) ଛାଡିଥିଲେ। କିନ୍ତୁ ଏହି ବଣ୍ଟନରେ ଅସୁବିଧା ଥିଲା।

A father, before his death, left a will (ଇଚ୍ଛାପତ୍ର) stating how his 35 camels (ଓଟ) should be divided among his three sons:
*   The eldest son (ବଡ ପୁଅ) was to receive $rac{1}{2}$ (one-half) of the camels.
*   The second son (ମଝିଆ ପୁଅ) was to receive $rac{1}{3}$ (one-third) of the camels.
*   The youngest son (ସାନ ପୁଅ) was to receive $rac{1}{9}$ (one-ninth) of the camels.

The brothers faced a significant difficulty (ଅସୁବିଧା) because dividing 35 camels by these fractions resulted in non-whole numbers. For example:
*   Eldest son: $rac{1}{2} \times 35 = 17.5$ camels
*   Second son: $rac{1}{3} \times 35 \approx 11.66$ camels (little less than 12)
*   Youngest son: $rac{1}{9} \times 35 \approx 3.88$ camels (little less than 4)

It is impossible to divide a living camel into fractions without harming it, leading to a quarrel (କଳି) among the brothers.

## The Clever Solution
ଓଡ଼ିଆ: ଏହି ସମସ୍ୟାର ସମାଧାନ ପାଇଁ ଜଣେ ଯୁବକ ତାଙ୍କର ନିଜ ଓଟକୁ ୩୫ଟି ଓଟ ସହିତ ମିଶାଇଲେ, ଯାହା ଫଳରେ ମୋଟ ଓଟ ସଂଖ୍ୟା ୩୬ ହେଲା।

A young man, often referred to as a "math-man" due to his intelligence (ବୁଦ୍ଧିମତା) in solving this problem, listened to their quarrel. He proposed a simple yet brilliant solution: he added his own camel to their herd (ପଲ). This increased the total number of camels from 35 to $35 + 1 = 36$.

## The New Division and Outcome
ଓଡ଼ିଆ: ୩୬ଟି ଓଟକୁ ଭାଗ କରିବା ସହଜ ହେଲା। ପ୍ରତ୍ୟେକ ପୁଅକୁ ପୂର୍ଣ୍ଣ ସଂଖ୍ୟାରେ ଓଟ ମିଳିଲା ଏବଂ ସମସ୍ତେ ଖୁସି ହେଲେ।

With 36 camels, the division became straightforward (ସହଜ):
*   **Eldest son:** $rac{1}{2}$ of $36 = 18$ camels. (He was to get $17.5$, so he received more and was happy.)
*   **Second son:** $rac{1}{3}$ of $36 = 12$ camels. (He was to get less than $12$, so he received more and was happy.)
*   **Youngest son:** $rac{1}{9}$ of $36 = 4$ camels. (He was to get less than $4$, so he received more and was happy.)

All three brothers were happy with their shares (ଭାଗ).

## The Math-Man's Gain and the "Magic"
ଓଡ଼ିଆ: ଓଟ ବଣ୍ଟନ ପରେ, ମୋଟ ୩୪ଟି ଓଟ ଭାଇମାନଙ୍କୁ ମିଳିଲା। ବାକି ଥିବା ଓଟ ମଧ୍ୟରୁ ଯୁବକ ଜଣକ ନିଜ ଓଟ ଫେରି ପାଇଲେ ଏବଂ ଅଧିକ ଗୋଟିଏ ଓଟ ମଧ୍ୟ ପାଇଲେ। ଏହା ଗଣିତର ଯାଦୁ।

After the division, the total number of camels distributed among the brothers was $18 + 12 + 4 = 34$ camels.
Since the total herd was 36 camels, and 34 were given to the brothers, $36 - 34 = 2$ camels remained.
The young math-man took back his own camel. The text states, "By solving their problem, he himself got a camel." This implies that one of the remaining camels was his, and he also gained another camel for his cleverness. The text says "The young math-man gained one though he had no camel of his own." This means he got one of the two remaining camels.

This entire solution highlights the "magic of knowing mathematics" (ଗଣିତର ଯାଦୁ). The key mathematical insight is that the sum of the fractions in the father's will is less than one:
$$
rac{1}{2} + rac{1}{3} + rac{1}{9} = rac{9}{18} + rac{6}{18} + rac{2}{18} = rac{17}{18}
$$
Because the sum is $rac{17}{18}$ (less than a whole), there was always a portion of the original 35 camels that was not explicitly willed to the sons. By temporarily increasing the total to 36, the fractions could be applied cleanly, and the "extra" camel (or camels) allowed for a perfect distribution and a gain for the solver.

